      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the goblin overload! You are absolutely right; I got carried away with the metaphorical goblin diet and cookie trading. Let's get back to the actual math and mechanics of how ARM rates work.\n\nHere is the breakdown of how an Adjustable-Rate Mortgage (ARM) actually changes your payments after the initial period:\n\n1.  **The Index:** Your ARM rate is built on top of a specific \"index\" (like the SOFR or Prime Rate). This index fluctuates daily based on market conditions.\n2.  **The Margin:** You add a fixed \"margin\" (usually 0.5% to 2%) to that index. This margin is set when you sign the loan and never changes.\n3.  **The Cap:** The rate can only move up or down by a certain percentage at a time (Period Cap) and over the life of the loan (Lifetime Cap).\n4.  **The Adjustment:** After your initial period (e.g., 5 years), the rate recalculates annually. If the index goes up by 0.5% and your margin is 1%, your rate might jump by 1.5% (subject to caps).",
